Text_origin: The Khaleefeh Hároon Er-Rasheed had gone forth this night to see and hear what news he could collect, accompanied by Jaạfar his Wezeer, and Mesroor his executioner. It was his custom to disguise himself in the attire of a merchant; and this night, as he went through the city, he happened to pass, with his attendants, by the house of these ladies, and hearing the sounds of the musical instruments, he said to Jaạfar, I have a desire to enter this house, and to see who is giving this concert. They are a party who have become intoxicated, replied Jaạfar, and I fear that we may experience some ill usage from them; but the Khaleefeh said, We must enter, and I would that thou devise some stratagem by which we may obtain admission to the inmates. Jaạfar therefore answered, I hear and obey: and he advanced, and knocked at the door; and when the portress came and opened the door, he said to her, My mistress, we are merchants from Tabareeyeh, and have been in Baghdád ten days; we have brought with us merchandise, and taken lodgings in a Khán; and a merchant invited us to an entertainment this night: accordingly, we went to his house, and he placed food before us, and we ate, and sat awhile drinking together, after which he gave us leave to depart; and going out in the dark, and being strangers, we missed our way to the Khán: we trust, therefore, in your generosity that you will admit us to pass the night in your house; by doing which you will obtain a reward in heaven.

Text_origin: Bhí an Khaleefeh Hároon Er-Rasheed imithe amach an oíche seo chun an nuacht a d’fhéadfadh sé a bhailiú a fheiceáil agus a chloisteáil, in éineacht le Jaạfar a Wezeer, agus Mesroor a fhorghníomhaitheoir. Ba é an nós a bhí aige é féin a cheilt in éadaí ceannaí; agus an oíche seo, agus é ag dul tríd an gcathair, tharla sé pas a fháil, lena lucht freastail, ag teach na mban seo, agus fuaimeanna na n-uirlisí ceoil a chloisteáil, a dúirt sé le Jaạfar, tá fonn orm dul isteach sa teach seo, agus le feiceáil cé atá ag tabhairt na ceolchoirme seo. Is páirtí iad atá ar meisce, a d’fhreagair Jaạfar, agus is eagal liom go bhféadfaimis drochúsáid éigin a bhaint astu; ach dúirt an Khaleefeh, Caithfimid dul isteach, agus ba mhaith liom go gceapfá stratagem éigin trínar féidir linn iontráil a fháil do na háitritheoirí. Mar sin d’fhreagair Jaạfar, cloisim agus géillim: agus chuaigh sé chun cinn, agus bhuail sé ag an doras; agus nuair a tháinig an portóir agus a d’oscail sé an doras, dúirt sé léi, A mháistir, is ceannaithe as Tabareeyeh muid, agus bhíomar i mBagdád deich lá; tá marsantas tugtha againn linn, agus lóistín a thógáil i Khán; agus thug ceannaí cuireadh dúinn chuig siamsaíocht an oíche seo: dá réir sin, chuamar go dtí a theach, agus chuir sé bia os ár gcomhair, agus d’itheamar, agus shuíomar go huafásach ag ól le chéile, agus ina dhiaidh sin thug sé cead dúinn imeacht; agus ag dul amach sa dorchadas, agus a bheith inár strainséirí, chaill muid ár mbealach chuig an Khán: tá muinín againn, mar sin, i do fhlaithiúlacht go n-admhóidh tú dúinn an oíche a chaitheamh i do theach; trína dhéanamh gheobhaidh tú luaíocht ar neamh.
Text_en: The Khaleefeh Hároon Er-Rasheed had gone out this night to see and hear the news he could collect, along with Jaạfar a Wezeer, and Mesroor his executioner. So Jaạfar answered, I hear and obey: and he went forward, and knocked at the door; and when the porter came and opened the door, he said to her, Master, we are merchants of Tabareeyeh, and we were in Baghdad ten days; we have brought merchandise with us, and build lodgings in Khán; and a merchant invited us to entertainment this night: accordingly, we went to his house, and he presented us with food, and we ate, and we sat dreadfully drinking together, and afterwards he gave permission for us to leave; and going out into darkness, and being our strangers, we lost our way to the Khán: we trust therefore in your generosity that you will acknowledge us for spending the night in your home; by doing it you will be rewarded in heaven.

Text_origin: U-Khaleefeh Tuberoon u-Er-Rasheed ubephume ngalobu busuku ezobona futhi ezwe izindaba angaziqoqa, kanye noJaạfar a Wezeer, noMesroor owayebulala yena. Kwakuyisiko lakhe ukuzifihla ngezingubo zomthengisi; futhi ngalobu busuku, lapho edlula edolobheni, kwenzeka, kanye nezinceku zakhe, endlini yalo wesifazane, futhi ukuzwa umsindo wezinto zomculo, watshela uJaạfar, ngifisa ukungena kulendlu, nokubona ukuthi ubani opha le khonsathi. Lapho umgcini-mnyango efika futhi evula umnyango, wathi kuye: “Mfundisi, singabathengisi baseThabareeyeh, futhi besiseBaghdad izinsuku eziyishumi; silethile ngokuthengisa nathi, futhi sakhe izindawo zokuhlala eKhán; futhi umthengisi wasimema ukuba sizokuzijabulisa ngalobu busuku: ngakho-ke, sahamba saya endlini yakhe, wasiletha ukudla, sadla, sahlala saphuza ngokudabukisayo, futhi kamuva wavumela ukuthi sihambe; futhi siphume siye ebumnyameni, futhi njengabafokazi bethu, sehle sahamba saya eKhan: ngakho-ke sethembela emseni wakho wokuthi uzosivuma ngokuchitha ubusuku ekhaya lakho; ngokwenza kanjalo uzovuzwa ezulwini.
Text_en: Er-Rasheed's Khaleefeh Tuberoon was out tonight to see and hear the stories he could collect, along with Jaạfar a Wezeer, and Mesroor who was killing himself. When the doorkeeper came and opened the door, he said to him: “Teacher, we are merchants of Thabareeyeh, and we have been in Baghdad for ten days; we have brought it to market with us, and built shelters in Khán; and the merchant invited us to entertain us this night: and so, we went to his house, brought us food, ate, sat down sadly, and later let us go; and out into the darkness, and like our aliens, we went down to Canaan: and therefore we trust in thy grace that thou wilt admit us to spend the night in thy house; in so doing you will be rewarded in heaven.

Text_origin: كان خليفة خليفة رشيد رشيد في الخارج الليلة لرؤية وسماع القصص التي يمكن أن يجمعها ، إلى جانب جعفر ويزر ، وميسرور الذي كان يقتل نفسه. كان من عادته إخفاء ملابس التاجر. وفي تلك الليلة ، وهو يمر عبر المدينة ، حدث ذلك ، مع خدمه ، إلى منزل السيدة ، وسماع صوت الآلات الموسيقية ، أخبر جعفر ، راغبًا في دخول هذا المنزل ، ومعرفة من قدم الحفل. يجيب جعفر ، إنهم حزب مخمور ، وأخشى أن نسيء إليهم. لكن الخليفة قال ، يجب أن ندخل ، وأريدك أن تحدد بعض الطرق التي يمكننا من خلالها دخول المواطنين. فأجاب جعفر: "أسمع وأطيع." عندما جاء البواب وفتح الباب قال له: يا معلم ، نحن تجار من الثبارية ، وكنا في بغداد منذ عشرة أيام. أدخلناها إلى السوق وأقمنا ملاجئ في خان ؛ ودعانا التاجر للترفيه عننا هذه الليلة: وهكذا ذهبنا إلى منزله وجلبنا الطعام وأكلنا وجلسنا حزينًا ، ثم تركنا نذهب ؛ وخرجنا إلى الظلام ، ومثل كائناتنا الفضائية ، نزلنا إلى كنعان ، وبالتالي نثق في نعمتك التي ستعترف بها لقضاء الليل في بيتك ؛ وبذلك ستكافأ في السماء.

Text_origin: ממשיכו של ח'ליפה ראשיד היה הלילה לראות ולשמוע את הסיפורים שיכול היה לאסוף יחד עם ג'עפר וויסר ומיסור שהרג את עצמו. היה זה מנהגו להסתיר את בגדי הסוחר. ובאותו לילה, כשעבר בעיר, זה קרה, עם משרתיו, לבית הגברת, וכששמע צליל כלי נגינה, הוא אמר לג'עפר, שהוא רוצה להיכנס לבית הזה, ולברר מי הציג את המסיבה. ג'עפר מגיב: "הם מפלגה שיכורה, ואני חושש שנתעלב בהם." אבל הח'ליף אמר: עלינו להיכנס, ואני רוצה שתפרט כמה דרכים בהן אנו יכולים להיכנס לאזרחים. ג'עפר ענה, "אני מקשיב ואני מציית." כשהגיע השוער ופתח את הדלת, הוא אמר: אדון, אנחנו סוחרים מאל-תעבריה, והיינו בבגדאד לפני עשרה ימים. לקחנו אותו לשוק והקמנו מקלטים בחאן, והסוחר הזמין אותנו לבדר את עצמנו הלילה: אז הלכנו לביתו, הבאנו אוכל, אכלנו וישבנו עצובים, ואז שחררנו; בביתך, ובדרך זו תתוגמלים בשמיים.
